WEBVTT

00:00.355 --> 00:01.787
<i>Previously on</i>
The Big Bang Theory...

00:01.950 --> 00:04.258
We conclusively proved
super-asymmetry,

00:04.259 --> 00:07.406
and yet somehow
we-we still feel like imposters.

00:07.407 --> 00:09.173
Yeah, there should be
a term for that.

00:09.242 --> 00:11.909
Oh, for crying out loud,
there is a term for that!

00:11.978 --> 00:14.011
It's called
"imposter syndrome,"

00:14.080 --> 00:16.079
and you don't have it,
because you can't have it

00:16.149 --> 00:18.349
if you are imposters,
and you are!

00:18.418 --> 00:21.285
We're the ones who discovered
super-asymmetry,

00:21.354 --> 00:23.674
so if anyone's gonna feel like
they have imposter syndrome,

00:23.723 --> 00:27.458
it's us because we're
not imposters, they are!

00:27.527 --> 00:30.461
You're imposters
and you're frauds!

00:33.466 --> 00:35.833
I think what President Siebert
is trying to say is that

00:35.902 --> 00:38.669
this is a setback and we should
adopt a different strategy.

00:38.738 --> 00:41.305
I-I'm sorry.
I-I just-- I-I snapped.

00:41.374 --> 00:43.941
Oh, you're sorry.
It's all better, then.

00:44.010 --> 00:46.777
Listen up, you have shot
to win a Nobel Prize,

00:46.846 --> 00:48.179
and you're blowing it.

00:48.248 --> 00:50.381
I think what President Siebert
is trying to say

00:50.450 --> 00:52.817
is that you have a shot
to win a Nobel Prize,

00:52.886 --> 00:55.419
and you're blowing it.

00:55.488 --> 00:58.856
Uh, that's exactly
what he said.

00:58.925 --> 01:02.160
Yes, but I said it
in my calming HR voice.

01:05.137 --> 01:07.114
So, obviously,

01:07.115 --> 01:09.315
I'm really sorry
about my outburst.

01:09.384 --> 01:11.584
Calling you frauds
was unacceptable.

01:11.653 --> 01:13.286
I feel terrible
about it.

01:13.355 --> 01:15.221
It has caused her
a lot of stress.

01:15.290 --> 01:16.723
She chewed through
her night guard

01:16.792 --> 01:19.492
like it was a
piece of jerky.

01:19.561 --> 01:21.394
What you said was
really hurtful,

01:21.463 --> 01:23.329
especially because I
thought we were friends.

01:23.398 --> 01:25.532
Why would you think that?

01:25.600 --> 01:28.535
Ouch.

01:28.603 --> 01:31.538
Ignore them;
they're just mean people.

01:31.606 --> 01:33.890
Uh, not mean, just sorry.

01:33.959 --> 01:37.210
Seem mean, are sorry.
Happens all the time.

01:37.279 --> 01:39.596
It's okay.
I talked to my therapist,

01:39.648 --> 01:41.581
and she made me realize
that what you said

01:41.650 --> 01:44.317
was really more about
your own insecurities.

01:46.254 --> 01:48.188
I'm sorry, what?

01:48.256 --> 01:50.623
There you go, she's sorry.
We all heard it. Moving on.

01:50.692 --> 01:52.625
Yes, obviously,

01:52.694 --> 01:54.627
you're angry at all
the attention we're getting

01:54.696 --> 01:56.629
for our discovery
and you're lashing out.

01:56.698 --> 01:59.499
Well, uh, technically,
<i>she</i> lashed out.

01:59.568 --> 02:01.801
<i>I</i> contained myself,
which I don't think

02:01.870 --> 02:04.070
I'm getting
enough credit for.

02:04.139 --> 02:06.439
The point is we should
take it as a compliment

02:06.508 --> 02:10.008
that even you guys think
we will win the Nobel Prize.

02:10.078 --> 02:13.279
Uh, no, we-we certainly
do not think that.

02:13.348 --> 02:14.814
The Nobel Committee
will realize

02:14.883 --> 02:16.416
that we came up
with this theory.

02:16.484 --> 02:17.484
But we proved it.

02:17.552 --> 02:18.651
By accident.

02:18.720 --> 02:21.254
All breakthroughs
happen by accident.

02:21.323 --> 02:23.990
No, they don't!

02:25.727 --> 02:27.388
Look, the Nobel Committee
doesn't like infighting,

02:27.412 --> 02:29.540
so if the four of you don't stop
sniping at each other,

02:29.564 --> 02:31.364
the award's gonna go
to someone else entirely.

02:31.433 --> 02:33.683
He's right.

02:33.752 --> 02:35.952
You know, like it or not,
we can't avoid each other.

02:36.021 --> 02:38.521
Let's at least
try to be civil.

02:38.590 --> 02:39.590
Agreed.

02:39.641 --> 02:41.407
You know, when you
think about it,

02:41.476 --> 02:45.184
we're linked together the
same way that super-asymmetry

02:45.185 --> 02:47.042
links together every atom
in the universe.

02:47.043 --> 02:48.560
Hmm.

02:48.561 --> 02:51.582
That's not
what it does at all!

02:52.040 --> 02:53.940
Well, that's the great thing
about science.

02:54.008 --> 02:56.609
We all get to have
our own opinions.

03:02.784 --> 03:04.149
I'm still not talking.
That's impressive, right?

